We have that $\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} \Rightarrow \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{0}.$

Using the properties of the cross product, we can rewrite this as

\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{a} &= \mathbf{0}.
\end{align*}

This means that $\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{b}$ is parallel to $\mathbf{a}$. Therefore, there exists a scalar $k$ such that

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{b} &= k\mathbf{a}.
\end{align*}

Solving for $\mathbf{v}$, we get

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} &= k\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

We also have that $\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$. Substituting the expression for $\mathbf{v}$, we get

\begin{align*}
(k\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}) \times \mathbf{b} &= \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

Expanding the cross products, we have

\begin{align*}
k(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) + \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{b} &= \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

Since $\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0}$, we have

\begin{align*}
k(\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) &= \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}.
\end{align*}

This means that $k = 1$. Therefore,

